      body: '“A signal and an instruction are not the same thing.”\n\n“A sensation appears.\nHeat.\nPressure.\nMovement.\nTension.\n\nThat is the signal.\n\nThen the system adds something else:\ncheck it.\nfix it.\nmonitor it.\nreact now.\n\nThat is the instruction.\n\nThe signal appeared first.\n\nThe obedience sequence followed after.\n\nMost people experience both together so quickly\nthey feel like one event.\n\nThey are not.\n\n***\n\nSignal:\n‘Something changed.’\n\nInstruction:\n‘Do something immediately.’\n\nSignal:\n‘The body reacted.’\n\nInstruction:\n‘This must be handled.’\n\n‘Awareness begins when the instruction becomes visible.’”',
    ),
    LibraryCardModel(
      id: 'Library_Workout3_Card2',
      title: 'Why the Sequence Feels Automatic',
      body: '“The instruction often arrives immediately after the signal.”\n\n“The system learned speed through repetition.\n\nA signal appears.\n\nThen the next move begins automatically.\n\nThis is why:\n- checking can feel immediate\n- monitoring can feel automatic\n- fixing can feel urgent\n- reaction can feel built into the sensation\n\nBut the reaction was not contained inside the signal itself.\n\nThe sequence formed afterward.\n\nThis is important.\n\nBecause what forms afterward\ncan become visible.\n\nAnd what becomes visible\ncan become interruptible.\n\n‘Automatic does not mean inseparable.’”',
